  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Through FY2026 to date, federal contract obligations in Missouri total $8.3B across 84,575 awards with an average award size of $98.5K; current-year totals are partial. Obligations fell 40.4% year over year. The Department of Defense accounts for the largest share of obligations at $5.5B, followed by the Department of Energy at $2B. Top vendors include THE BOEING COMPANY with $3.5B and HONEYWELL FEDERAL MANUFACTURING & TECHNOLOGIES, LLC with $2B, while industry concentrations are highest in Aircraft Manufacturing ($2.4B) and Facilities Support Services ($2.1B). Fiscal-year comparisons show that FY26 to date at $8.3B is below recent peak years such as FY24 at $16.2B and FY23 at $15.6B. Other notable FY2026 to date amounts include Direct Health and Medical Insurance Carriers at $642M, Ammunition (except Small Arms) Manufacturing at $633M, and Other Aircraft Parts and Auxiliary Equipment Manufacturing at $499M. These figures reflect partial fiscal-year activity and a substantial year-over-year contraction in obligations.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "How did obligations change year over year?",
        "body": "Obligations fell 40.4% year over year. FY26 to date obligations total $8.3B, down from FY25 at $14B and from FY24 at $16.2B, indicating a notable reduction in spending so far this fiscal year. The FY26 total is a partial (fiscal year to date) figure."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Who are the largest buyers and vendors in Missouri?",
        "body": "The Department of Defense is the largest buyer with $5.5B, followed by the Department of Energy with $2B and several agencies with lower totals such as the Department of Veterans Affairs at $194M and the Department of Agriculture at $185M. Leading vendors are THE BOEING COMPANY ($3.5B and a separate listing at $625M) and HONEYWELL FEDERAL MANUFACTURING & TECHNOLOGIES, LLC ($2B), with EVERNORTH FEDERAL SERVICES INC at $642M and WORLD WIDE TECHNOLOGY LLC at $133M among other top suppliers."
      }
    ]
